# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mbed-os
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The **ARM Cortex-M** is a group of 32-bit RISC ARM processor cores licensed by ARM Limited.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] These cores are optimized for low-cost and energy-efficient integrated circuits, which have been embedded in tens of billions of consumer devices.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Though they are most often the main component of microcontroller chips, sometimes they are embedded inside other types of chips too.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M family consists of Cortex-M0, Cortex-M0+, Cortex-M1, Cortex-M3, Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7, Cortex-M23, Cortex-M33, Cortex-M35P, Cortex-M52, Cortex-M55, Cortex-M85.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] A floating-point unit (FPU) option is available for Cortex-M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 cores, and when included in the silicon these cores are sometimes known as "Cortex-MxF", where 'x' is the core variant.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The ARM Cortex-M family are ARM microprocessor cores that are designed for use in microcontrollers, ASICs, ASSPs, FPGAs, and SoCs.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M cores are commonly used as dedicated microcontroller chips, but also are "hidden" inside of SoC chips as power management controllers, I/O controllers, system controllers, touch screen controllers, smart battery controllers, and sensor controllers.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The main difference from Cortex-A cores is that Cortex-M cores have no memory management unit (MMU) for virtual memory, considered essential for "full-fledged" operating systems.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M programs instead run bare metal or on one of the many real-time operating systems which support a Cortex-M.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Though 8-bit microcontrollers were very popular in the past, Cortex-M has slowly been chipping away at the 8-bit market as the prices of low-end Cortex-M chips have moved downward.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Cortex-M have become a popular replacements for 8-bit chips in applications that benefit from 32-bit math operations, and replacing older legacy ARM cores such as ARM7 and ARM9.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] In particular, the embedded wear-leveling controller inside most SD cards or flash drives is a (8-bit) 8051 microcontroller or ARM CPU.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] ARM Limited neither manufactures nor sells CPU devices based on its own designs, but rather licenses the processor architecture to interested parties.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Arm offers a variety of licensing terms, varying in cost and deliverables.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] To all licensees, Arm provides an integratable hardware description of the ARM core, as well as complete software development toolset and the right to sell manufactured silicon containing the ARM CPU.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Integrated Device Manufacturers (IDM) receive the ARM Processor IP as synthesizable RTL (written in Verilog).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] In this form, they have the ability to perform architectural level optimizations and extensions.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] This allows the manufacturer to achieve custom design goals, such as higher clock speed, very low power consumption, instruction set extensions (including floating point), optimizations for size, debug support, etc.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] To determine which components have been included in a particular ARM CPU chip, consult the manufacturer datasheet and related documentation.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The architectures are binary instruction upward compatible from ARMv6-M to ARMv7-M to ARMv7E-M.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M3 / Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Binary instructions available for the Cortex-M3 can execute without modification on the Cortex-M4 / Cortex-M7 / Cortex-M33 / Cortex-M35P.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Only Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instruction sets are supported in Cortex-M architectures; the legacy 32-bit ARM instruction set isn't supported.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] All Cortex-M cores implement a common subset of instructions that consists of most Thumb-1, some Thumb-2, including a 32-bit result multiply.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / Cortex-M0+ / Cortex-M1 / Cortex-M23 were designed to create the smallest silicon die, thus having the fewest instructions of the Cortex-M family.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include Thumb-1 instructions, except new instructions (CBZ, CBNZ, IT) which were added in ARMv7-M architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 / M0+ / M1 include a minor subset of Thumb-2 instructions (BL, DMB, DSB, ISB, MRS, MSR).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 / M4 / M7 / M33 / M35P have all base Thumb-1 and Thumb-2 instructions.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M3 adds three Thumb-1 instructions, all Thumb-2 instructions, hardware integer divide, and saturation arithmetic instructions.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M4 adds DSP instructions and an optional single-precision floating-point unit (VFPv4-SP).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 adds an optional double-precision FPU (VFPv5).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 / M33 / M35P / M52 / M55 / M85 add TrustZone instructions.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The 16-bit Thumb-1 instruction set has evolved over time since it was first released in the legacy ARM7T cores with the ARMv4T architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] New Thumb-1 instructions were added as each legacy ARMv5 / ARMv6 / ARMv6T2 architectures were released.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0 core is optimized for small silicon die size and use in the lowest price chips.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ is an optimized superset of the Cortex-M0.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ has complete instruction set compatibility with the Cortex-M0 thus allowing the use of the same compiler and debug tools.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ pipeline was reduced from 3 to 2 stages, which lowers the power usage and increases performance (higher average IPC due to branches taking one fewer cycle).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] In addition to debug features in the existing Cortex-M0, a silicon option can be added to the Cortex-M0+ called the Micro Trace Buffer (MTB) which provides a simple instruction trace buffer.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M0+ also received Cortex-M3 and Cortex-M4 features, which can be added as silicon options, such as the memory protection unit (MPU) and the vector table relocation.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The smallest ARM microcontrollers are of the Cortex-M0+ type (as of 2014, smallest at 1.6 mm by 2 mm in a chip-scale package is Kinetis KL03).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M1 is an optimized core especially designed to be loaded into FPGA chips.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M4 is a Cortex-M3 plus DSP instructions, and optional floating-point unit (FPU).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] A core with an FPU is known as Cortex-M4F.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M7 is a high-performance core with almost double the power efficiency of the older Cortex-M4.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] It features a 6-stage superscalar pipeline with branch prediction and an optional floating-point unit capable of single-precision and optionally double-precision operations.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The instruction and data buses have been enlarged to 64-bit wide over the previous 32-bit buses.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] If a core contains an FPU, it is known as a Cortex-M7F, otherwise it is a Cortex-M7.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M23 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M23 is similar to a Cortex-M0+ plus integer divide instructions and TrustZone security features, and also has a 2-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M33 core was announced in October 2016 and based on the ARMv8-M architecture that was previously announced in November 2015.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually the Cortex-M33 is similar to a cross of Cortex-M4 and Cortex-M23, and also has a 3-stage instruction pipeline.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M35P core was announced in May 2018 and based on the Armv8-M architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] It is conceptually a Cortex-M33 core with a new instruction cache, plus new tamper-resistant hardware concepts borrowed from the ARM SecurCore family, and configurable parity and ECC features.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Currently, information about the Cortex-M35P is limited, because its *Technical Reference Manual* and *Generic User Guide* haven't been released yet.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M52 core was announced in November 2023 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Conceptually, it can be seen as a cross between the Cortex-M33 and the Cortex-M55.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] Key differences are that its Helium co-processor is single beat (the M55 is dual beat), and it has a 32-bit main bus similar to the M33 to ease transition of applications.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M55 core was announced in February 2020 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] It has a 4 or 5 stage instruction pipeline.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The Cortex-M85 core was announced in April 2022 and based on the Armv8.1-M architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] The documentation for ARM chips is extensive.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] In the past, 8-bit microcontroller documentation would typically fit in a single document, but as microcontrollers have evolved, so has everything required to support them.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] A documentation package for ARM chips typically consists of a collection of documents from the IC manufacturer as well as the CPU core vendor (ARM Limited).
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer datasheet for the exact physical chip.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturer reference manual that describes common peripherals and aspects of a physical chip family.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] IC manufacturers have additional documents, such as: evaluation board user manuals, application notes, getting started guides, software library documents, errata, and more.
[src:mbed-os/arm-cortex-m] See External links section for links to official Arm documents.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] "ARM" was originally an acronym for Acorn RISC Machine and later for Advanced RISC Machines.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] While ARM CPUs first appeared in the Acorn Archimedes, a desktop computer, today's systems include mostly embedded systems, including ARM CPUs used in virtually all modern smartphones.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Processors based on designs licensed from Arm, or designed by licensees of one of the ARM instruction set architectures, are used in all classes of computing devices.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm has two lines of graphics processing units (GPUs), Mali, and the newer Immortalis (which includes hardware-based ray-tracing).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm's main CPU competitors in servers include IBM, Intel and AMD.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Intel competed with ARM-based chips in mobile devices but Arm no longer has any competition in that space (although vendors of actual ARM-based chips compete within that arena).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm's main GPU competitors include mobile GPUs from technology companies Imagination Technologies (PowerVR), Qualcomm (Adreno), and increasingly Nvidia, AMD, Samsung and Intel.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] While competing in GPUs, Qualcomm, Samsung and Nvidia all have combined their GPUs with Arm-licensed CPUs.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm had a primary listing on the London Stock Exchange (LSE) and was a constituent of the FTSE 100 Index.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] It also had a secondary listing of American depositary receipts on New York's Nasdaq.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] However, Japanese multinational conglomerate SoftBank Group made an agreed offer for Arm on 18 July 2016, subject to approval by Arm's shareholders, valuing the company at £24.3 billion.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The transaction was completed on 5 September 2016.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] A planned takeover deal by Nvidia, announced in 2020, collapsed in February 2022, with SoftBank subsequently deciding to pursue an initial public offering on the Nasdaq in 2023, valuing Arm at US$54.5 billion.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The acronym ARM was first used in 1983 and originally stood for "Acorn RISC Machine".
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Acorn Computers' first RISC processor was used in the original Acorn Archimedes and was one of the first RISC processors used in small computers.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] However, when the company was incorporated in 1990, what 'ARM' stood for changed to "Advanced RISC Machines".
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] According to Steve Furber the name was changed at the behest of Apple, which did not wish to have the name of a competitor in the name of the company.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] At the time of the IPO in 1998, the company name was changed to "ARM Holdings", often just called ARM like the processors.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 1 August 2017, the styling and logo were changed.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The logo is now all lowercase ('arm') and other uses of the name are in sentence case ('Arm').
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The company was founded on 12 November 1990 as **Widelogic Limited** but this was rapidly changed, on 3 December 1990, to **Advanced RISC Machines Limited** and structured as a joint venture between Acorn Computers, Apple, and VLSI Technology.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Acorn provided 12 employees, VLSI provided tools, Apple provided a US$3 million investment (equivalent to $7 million in 2025).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Larry Tesler, Apple VP was a key person and he helped recruit the first CEO at the joint venture, Robin Saxby.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The new company intended to further the development of the Acorn RISC Machine processor, which was originally used in the Acorn Archimedes and had been selected by Apple for its Newton project.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The company's Silicon Valley and Tokyo offices were opened in 1994.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] ARM invested in Palmchip Corporation in 1997 to provide system on chip platforms and to enter into the disk drive market.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In 1998, the company changed its name from *Advanced RISC Machines Ltd* to *ARM Ltd*.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The company was first listed on the London Stock Exchange (LSE) and Nasdaq in 1998 and by February 1999, Apple's shareholding had fallen to 14.8 per cent.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In 2010, ARM joined with IBM, Texas Instruments, Samsung, ST-Ericsson (since dissolved) and Freescale Semiconductor (now NXP Semiconductors) in forming a non-profit open source engineering company, Linaro.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] ARM also acquired the engineering team of PowerEscape.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In July 2020, Arm announced plans to spin off Treasure Data, together with the other parts of its "IoT Services Group" business, into separate SoftBank-owned entities by the end of September 2020.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] completed the acquisition of Arm Artisan Foundation IP, which ARM originally acquired from Artisan Components in 2004.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In May 2026, Bloomberg News reported that Arm Holdings and its majority owner, SoftBank Group, had made a preliminary approach to acquire the wafer-scale integrated circuit maker Cerebras Systems, in the weeks before Cerebras's planned initial public offering.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] According to the report, the approach was rebuffed.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Japanese conglomerate SoftBank Group made an agreed offer for ARM on 18 July 2016, subject to approval by ARM's shareholders, valuing the company at £23.4 billion (US$32 billion).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In 2017, a 25% stake of Arm was transferred to the SoftBank Vision Fund, which received investment from the Saudi sovereign fund.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] American technology company Nvidia announced plans on 13 September 2020 to acquire ARM from SoftBank, pending regulatory approval, for a value of US$40 billion in stock and cash, which would have been the largest semiconductor acquisition to that date.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] SoftBank Group would acquire slightly less than a 10% stake in Nvidia, and ARM would maintain its headquarters in Cambridge.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] There was opposition to the deal, including national security concerns from the UK and competition concerns from fellow tech companies such as Google, Microsoft and Qualcomm, whose chips in use or on sale heavily rely on Arm's intellectual property.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] It was also being battled by Arm China, its subsidiary, a majority stake of which was held by Chinese investors.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The acquisition was initially scheduled to conclude before the end of 2022 per the contract.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] However, the European Commission, the UK Competition and Markets Authority and the US Federal Trade Commission raised completion concerns focusing on Arm's role within Nvidia, while the UK government also raised concerns about national security.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The merger attempt was eventually cancelled in February 2022 due to the aforementioned regulatory pressure and hurdles.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm filed for an IPO on 21 August 2023 on the Nasdaq, rather than the LSE.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] A few days earlier, SoftBank Group bought back the 25% stake from Vision Fund for around $16 billion, valuing Arm at over $64 billion.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm went public on 14 September 2023 raising $4.87 billion at a $54.5 billion valuation, with SoftBank continuing to own roughly 90% of the company following the offering.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] SoftBank Group sold more than half of Arm China in 2018 to a local consortium consisting of various parties including China Investment Corp. and the Silk Road Fund, effectively relinquishing majority ownership of its Chinese subsidiary to a group of investors with ties to the Chinese state.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] From 2020, discord between Arm and the effective owners of Arm China became visible after the British parent company unsuccessfully tried to oust the chief executive of the subsidiary, who, however, managed to retain his position.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] A prevailing view emerged that the matter would negatively affect the pending approval by the Chinese regulators of the SoftBank–Nvidia deal, as well as any public offering of Arm.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In September 2021, despite Arm's denial, reports stated that the chief executive of Arm China, whom the British parent had tried to dismiss, had publicly declared the "independence" of Arm China.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In February 2022, Allen Wu, the CEO of Arm China, floated the idea of a public offering of the Chinese subsidiary in 2025.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 29 April 2022, it was reported that the CEO and legal representative of Arm China had finally been replaced according to legally recognized filings.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] However, Allen Wu continued to dispute this.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Subsequently, in 2023, key staff left to form their own chip design startup Borui Jingxin, which competes with Arm China, particularly for engineers.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] This model is similar to those of fellow British design houses ARC International and Imagination Technologies, which have similarly been designing and licensing GPUs, CPUs, and SoCs, along with supplying tooling and various design and support services to its licensees.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] A characteristic feature of Arm processors is their low electric power consumption, which makes them particularly suitable for use in portable devices.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm processors are used as the main CPU for most mobile phones many PDAs and handhelds, like the Apple iPod and iPad, and computer games and as well as many other applications, including GPS navigation devices, digital cameras and televisions.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The world's second fastest supercomputer (previously fastest) in 2022, the Japanese Fugaku is based on Arm AArch64 architecture.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The supercomputer maker Cray has added an "ARM Option" (i.e.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] CPU blade option, using Cavium ThunderX2) to its XC50 supercomputers, and Cray claims that ARM is "a third processor architecture for building next-generation supercomputers", for clients such as the United States Department of Energy.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] These processors will also implement extensions to the ARMv8 architecture equivalent to HPC-ACE2 that Fujitsu is developing with ARM Holdings.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The Cray XC50-series supercomputer for the University of Bristol is called Isambard, named after Isambard Kingdom Brunel.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The supercomputer is expected to feature around 160 nodes, each with two 32-core ThunderX2 processors running at 2.1 GHz.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Peak theoretical performance of the 10,240 cores and 40,960 threads is 172 teraFLOPS.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The Vanguard project by Sandia National Laboratories is to deliver an exascale ARM machine.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The first generation called Hammer was based on X-Gene by Applied Micro.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The second generation called Sullivan was based Cavium's ThunderXs processors.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The third generation called **Mayer** was based on pre-production ThunderX2.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The fourth generation also based on ThunderX2 is called **Astra** and was slated to become operational by November 2018.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] ARM968E-S was used to build the neuromorphic supercomputer, SpiNNaker (Spiking Neural Network Architecture).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] It also has two lines of graphics processing units (GPUs): Mali, and the newer Immortalis (with hardware-based ray-tracing).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In addition, it offers Ethos neural processing units (NPUs), Corelink/CoreSight System/SoC IP, and TrustZone/CryptoCell/SecurCore Security IP.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm offers several microprocessor core designs that have been "publicly licensed" for its newer "application processors" (non-microcontroller) used in such applications as smartphones and tablets.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Cores for ARMv8.2-A include the Cortex-A77, Cortex-A65AE, Cortex-A76, Cortex-A75 and Cortex-A55.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Cores for ARMv8-A include the Cortex-A73, Cortex-A72, Cortex-A32, Cortex-A35, Cortex-A57 and Cortex-A53.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] ARM's client roadmap includes Hercules in 2020 and Matterhorn in 2021.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Companies often license these designs from Arm to manufacture and integrate into their own *System on chip* (SoC) with other components such as GPUs (sometimes Arm's Mali) or modem/radio basebands (for mobile phones).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm offers multiple licensing programs for its cores.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm also offers Artisan POP IP, where Arm partners with foundries to provide physical implementation, which allows faster time to market.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In February 2016, Arm announced the Built on Arm Cortex Technology licence often shortened to Built on Cortex (BoC) licence.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] This licence allows companies to partner with Arm and make modifications to Arm Cortex designs.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] These design modifications will not be shared with other companies.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] These semi-custom core designs also have brand freedom, for example Kryo 280.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In addition to licences for its core designs and BoC licence, Arm offers an "architectural licence" for its instruction set architectures, allowing the licensees to design their own cores that implement one of those instruction sets.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] An Arm architectural licence is more costly than a regular Arm core licence.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The *Financial Times* reported in March 2023 that Arm had planned to charge the licensees royalties based on the value of the device, instead of the prior model based on the chip's value.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Processors based on designs licensed from Arm, or designed by licensees of one of the ARM instruction set architectures, are used in all classes of computing devices (including in space).
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Processors designed by Arm or by Arm licensees are used as microcontrollers in embedded systems, including real-time safety systems (cars' ABS), biometrics systems (fingerprint sensor), smart TVs (e.g.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Systems, including iPhone smartphones, frequently include many chips, from many different providers, that include one or more licensed Arm cores, in addition to those in the main Arm-based processor.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Arm's core designs are also used in chips that support many common network-related technologies in smartphones: Bluetooth, WiFi and broadband, in addition to corresponding equipment such as Bluetooth headsets, 802.11ac routers, and network providers' cellular LTE.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In 2011, Arm renewed a five-year, US$5 million research partnership with University of Michigan, which extended their existing research partnership to 2015.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] This partnership would focus on ultra-low energy and sustainable computing.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In October 2017, Arduino announced its partnership with ARM.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] The announcement said, in part, "ARM recognized independence as a core value of Arduino ... without any lock-in with the ARM architecture." Arduino intends to continue to work with all technology vendors and architectures.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In October 2018, ARM Holdings partnered with Intel in order to share code for embedded systems through the Yocto Project.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 12 April 2023, ARM Holdings partnered with Intel Foundry Services to bring Arm SoCs to Intel's 18A process.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 20 October 2018, Arm unveiled Arm Mbed OS, an open source operating system for IoT.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 8 October 2019, Arm announced a new Partner Governance model for partners to collaborate on the future roadmap.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Partners include: Analog Devices, Cypress, Maxim Integrated, Nuvoton, NXP, Renesas, Realtek, Samsung, Silicon Labs and u-blox.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In November 2020, Arm spun out the entire IoT software division as Pelion, a separate but wholly owned subsidiary of Arm.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In October 2022 the IoT services of Pelion were purchased by Izuma Networks, an Austin, Texas based startup.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 8 October 2019, Arm announced the Autonomous Vehicle Computing Consortium (AVCC) to collaborate and accelerate development of self-driving cars.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Members include Arm, Bosch, Continental, Denso, General Motors, Nvidia, NXP and Toyota.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In August 2020, Arm signed a three-year agreement with DARPA, the US Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency, enabling DARPA researchers to use all of Arm's commercially available technology.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In October 2001, Warren East was appointed chief executive officer (CEO) of Arm Holdings.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In the 2011 financial year, East received a total compensation of £1,187,500 from ARM, comprising a salary of £475,000 and a bonus of £712,500.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In May 2013, president Simon Segars took over as CEO.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] In March 2014, former Rexam chairman Stuart Chambers succeeded John Buchanan as chairman.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] Chambers, a non-executive director of Tesco and former chief executive of Nippon Sheet Glass Group, had previously worked at Mars and Royal Dutch Shell.
[src:mbed-os/arm-holdings] On 8 February 2022, Rene Haas succeeded Segars as CEO with immediate effect, with Segars leaving Arm.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] A precise and stable characteristic feature is that no or not all functions of embedded software are initiated/controlled via a human interface, but through machine-interfaces instead.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Manufacturers build embedded software into the electronics of cars, telephones, modems, robots, appliances, toys, security systems, pacemakers, televisions and set-top boxes, and digital watches, for example.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] This software can be very simple, such as lighting controls running on an 8-bit microcontroller with a few kilobytes of memory with the suitable level of processing complexity determined with a Probably Approximately Correct Computation framework (a methodology based on randomized algorithms).
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] However, embedded software can become very sophisticated in applications such as routers, optical network elements, airplanes, missiles, and process control systems.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Unlike standard computers that generally use operating systems such as macOS, Windows or Linux, embedded software may use no operating system.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] When they do use one, a wide variety of operating systems can be chosen from, typically a real-time operating system.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Code for embedded software is typically written in C or C++, but various high-level programming languages, such as C#, Java, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Assembly languages are often used too, especially in booting and interrupt handling.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Ada is used in some military and aviation projects.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Most consumers are familiar with application software that provide functionality on a computer.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] However embedded software is often less visible, but no less complicated.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Unlike application software, embedded software has fixed hardware requirements and capabilities, and addition of third-party hardware or software is strictly controlled.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Embedded software needs to include all needed device drivers at manufacturing time, and the device drivers are written for the various hardware devices.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] The software is highly dependent on the CPU and specific chips chosen.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Most embedded software engineers have at least a passing knowledge of reading schematics, and reading data sheets for components to determine usage of registers and communication system.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Conversion between decimal, hexadecimal and binary is useful as well as using bit manipulation.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Web applications are often used for managing hardware, although XML files and other output may be passed to a computer for display.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] File systems with folders are typically used, however SQL databases are often absent.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Software development requires use of a cross compiler, which runs on a computer but produces executable code for the target device.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Debugging requires use of an in-circuit emulator, and debugging hardware such as JTAG or SWD debuggers.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Software developers often have access to the complete kernel (OS) source code.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Size of the storage memory and RAM can vary significantly.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Some systems run in 16 KB of Flash and 4 KB of RAM with a CPU operating at 8 MHz, other systems can rival contemporary computers.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] These space requirements lead to more work being done in C or embedded C++, instead of C++.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Interpreted languages like BASIC (while e.g.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Parallax Propeller can use compiled BASIC) and Java (Java ME Embedded 8.3 is available for e.g.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] ARM Cortex-M4, Cortex-M7 microcontrollers and older ARM11 used in Raspberry Pi and Intel Galileo Gen.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] 2) are not commonly used; while an implementation of the interpreted Python 3 language – MicroPython – is however available expressly for microcontroller use, e.g.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] 32-bit ARM-based (such as BBC micro:bit) and 16-bit PIC microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Communications between processors and between one processor and other components are essential.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Besides direct memory addressing, hardware level common protocols include I²C, SPI, serial ports, 1-Wires, Ethernets, and USB.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Communications protocols designed for use in embedded systems are available as closed source from companies including InterNiche Technologies and CMX Systems.
[src:mbed-os/embedded-software] Open-source protocols stem from uIP, lwip, and others.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] In computing, **firmware** (**FW**) is software that provides low-level control of computer hardware.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] For a relatively simple device, firmware may perform all control, monitoring and data manipulation functionality.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] For a more complex device, firmware may provide only relatively low-level control as well as hardware abstraction to higher-level software such as an operating system.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Firmware is found in a wide range of computing devices, including personal computers, smartphones, home appliances, vehicles, computer peripherals and in many of the integrated circuits inside each of these larger systems.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Firmware is stored in non-volatile memory – either read-only memory (ROM) or programmable memory such as EPROM, EEPROM, or flash.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Changing a device's firmware stored in ROM requires physically replacing the memory chip or the device itself.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Programmable firmware memory can be reprogrammed via a procedure sometimes called *flashing*.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Common reasons for changing firmware include fixing bugs and adding features.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Ascher Opler used the term *firmware* in a 1967 *Datamation* article, as an intermediary term between *hardware* and *software*.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Opler projected that fourth-generation computer systems would have a writable control store (a small specialized high-speed memory) into which microcode firmware would be loaded.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Many software functions would be moved to microcode, and instruction sets could be customized, with different firmware loaded for different instruction sets.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] As computers began to increase in complexity, it became clear that various programs needed to first be initiated and run to provide a consistent environment necessary for running more complex programs at the user's discretion.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] This required programming the computer to run those programs automatically.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Furthermore, as companies, universities, and marketers wanted to sell computers to laypeople with little technical knowledge, greater automation became necessary to allow a layperson to easily run programs for practical purposes.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] This gave rise to a kind of software that a user would not consciously run, and it led to software that a lay user would not even know about.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] As originally used, firmware contrasted with hardware (the CPU itself) and software (normal instructions executing on a CPU).
[src:mbed-os/firmware] It was not composed of CPU machine instructions, but of lower-level microcode involved in the implementation of machine instructions.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] It existed on the boundary between hardware and software; thus the name *firmware*.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] In some respects, the various firmware components are as important as the operating system in a working computer.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] However, unlike most modern operating systems, firmware rarely has a well-evolved automatic mechanism of updating itself to fix any functionality issues detected after shipping the unit.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] A computer's firmware may be manually updated by a user via a small utility program.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] In contrast, firmware in mass storage devices (hard-disk drives, optical disc drives, flash memory storage e.g., solid state drive) is less frequently updated, even when flash memory (rather than ROM, EEPROM) storage is used for the firmware.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Most computer peripherals are themselves special-purpose computers.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Devices such as printers, scanners, webcams, and USB flash drives have internally-stored firmware; some devices may also permit field upgrading of their firmware.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] For modern, simpler devices, such as USB keyboards, USB mouses and USB sound cards, the trend is to store the firmware in on-chip memory in the device's microcontroller, as opposed to storing it in a separate EEPROM chip.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Consumer products like digital cameras and portable music players support firmware upgrades.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] In digital cameras, firmware upgrades address bugs in the operation, along with adding new functions to the camera's operation.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Some companies use firmware updates to add new playable file formats (codecs).
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Other features that may change with firmware updates include the user interface or even the battery life.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Since 1996, most automobiles have employed an on-board computer and various sensors to detect mechanical problems.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] As of 2010, modern vehicles also employ computer-controlled anti-lock braking systems (ABS) and computer-operated transmission control units (TCUs).
[src:mbed-os/firmware] The driver can also get in-dash information while driving in this manner, such as real-time fuel economy and tire pressure readings.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Local dealers can update most vehicle firmware.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Sometimes, third parties develop an unofficial new or modified ("aftermarket") version of firmware to provide new features or to unlock hidden functionality; this is referred to as custom firmware.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] An example is Rockbox as a firmware replacement for portable media players.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] There are many homebrew projects for various devices, which often unlock general-purpose computing functionality in previously limited devices (e.g., running Doom on iPods).
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Firmware hacks usually take advantage of the firmware update facility on many devices to install or run themselves.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Some, however, must resort to exploits to run, because the manufacturer has attempted to lock the hardware to stop it from running unlicensed code.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Although the Kaspersky Lab report did not explicitly claim that this group is part of the United States National Security Agency (NSA), evidence obtained from the code of various Equation Group software suggests that they are part of the NSA.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Researchers from the Kaspersky Lab categorized the undertakings by Equation Group as the most advanced hacking operation ever uncovered, also documenting around 500 infections caused by the Equation Group in at least 42 countries.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Mark Shuttleworth, the founder of the company Canonical, which created the Ubuntu Linux distribution, has described proprietary firmware as a security risk, saying that "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend" and calling firmware "a trojan horse of monumental proportions".
[src:mbed-os/firmware] As a potential solution to this problem, he has called for declarative firmware, which would describe "hardware linkage and dependencies" and "should not include executable code".
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Firmware should be open-source so that the code can be checked and verified.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Custom firmware hacks have also focused on injecting malware into devices such as smartphones or USB devices.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] One such smartphone injection was demonstrated on the Symbian OS at MalCon, a hacker convention.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] A USB device firmware hack called BadUSB was presented at the Black Hat USA 2014 conference, demonstrating how a USB flash drive microcontroller can be reprogrammed to spoof various other device types to take control of a computer, exfiltrate data, or spy on the user.
[src:mbed-os/firmware] Other security researchers have worked further on how to exploit the principles behind BadUSB, releasing at the same time the source code of hacking tools that can be used to modify the behavior of different USB devices.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The full version is a real-time operating system (RTOS) while more resource constrained devices can opt to use a non-RTOS subset.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The primary way of developing Mbed applications is with the Arm Online Ide "Keil Studio Cloud" which is an online ide that uses cloud services to build and compile mbed applications.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Applications can be developed also with other development environments such as Keil μVision, IAR Embedded Workbench, Arduino IDE and Eclipse with GCC ARM Embedded tools.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed OS provides the Mbed C/C++ software platform and tools for creating microcontroller firmware that runs on IoT devices.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] It consists of the core libraries that provide the microcontroller peripheral drivers, networking, RTOS and runtime environment, build tools and test and debug scripts.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] These connections can be secured by compatible SSL/TLS libraries such as Mbed TLS or wolfSSL, which supports mbed-rtos.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] A components database provides driver libraries for components and services that can be connected to the microcontrollers to build a final product.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed OS, the RTOS, is based on Keil RTX5.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] There are various hardware demo-boards for the Mbed platform, with the first being the original Mbed Microcontroller board.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The Mbed Microcontroller Board (marketed as the "mbed NXP LPC1768") is a demo-board based on an NXP microcontroller, which has an ARM Cortex M3 core, running at 96 MHz, with 512 KB flash, 32 KB RAM, as well as several interfaces including Ethernet, USB Device, CAN, SPI, I2C and other I/O.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The Mbed microcontroller received first prize in the annual EDN Innovation Awards' Software/Embedded Tools category in 2010.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Various versions of the board were released, with NXP LPC2368 (ARM7TDMI-S), NXP LPC1768 (Cortex-M3), NXP LPC11U24 (Cortex-M0) microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The Mbed hardware development kit (HDK) is designed for OEMs, and provides information to build custom hardware to support Mbed OS.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] This consists of interface firmware and schematics that can be used to easily create development boards, OEM modules and re-programmable products suitable for production.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The project is developed by Arm in conjunction with other major technology companies and the Mbed developer community.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed OS supports, and has supported, a number of different development tools.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Applications for the Mbed platform could be developed using the Mbed online IDE, a free online code editor and compiler.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Only a web browser is needed to be installed on the local PC, since projects were compiled on the cloud, i.e. on a remote server, using the ARMCC C/C++ compiler.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The Mbed IDE provided private workspaces with ability to import, export, and share code with distributed Mercurial version control, and could be used also for code documentation generation.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed Online Compiler did not include any debugging functionality, and relied on a development cycle where users would download their compiled code as a .bin file, then manually copy it to an Mbed board (which appears as a USB flash drive).
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed Online Compiler was shut down on March 1, 2023, and replaced by Keil Studio Cloud.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] To satisfy the need for offline development of Mbed OS, ARM made available the Mbed CLI.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] This is a Python package that allows creating, importing, and compiling Mbed OS programs from the command line.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] It also integrates with external Git repositories and with Mbed's library repository, offering commands to download and update libraries from remote sources.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Internally, Mbed CLI consists of two different codebases.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The mbed-cli pip package, offering the mbed command, acts as a frontend that accepts commands from the user and is capable of downloading Mbed OS and libraries.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] In order to compile Mbed and software using it, the mbed-cli frontend calls into build tool scripts inside the mbed-os repository.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] These scripts are responsible for determining the correct compile options and executing the compiler and linker.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] After years of development, maintenance of the complex build tool scripts had become a significant burden to the Mbed OS developers.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] This led them to freeze the build tool code and work towards creating Mbed CLI 2 instead.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed Studio is a desktop IDE designed specifically to work with Mbed OS.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] First released in February 2019, Mbed Studio offered a more fully featured editing experience than the online compiler, including intelligent code completion functionality and debugging support.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Like the online compiler, it contains built-in support for creating new Mbed projects and declaring dependencies on libraries from Git repositories and Mbed's library repository.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] For its C/C++ compiler, Mbed Studio uses Arm Compiler 6, specially licensed by ARM for inclusion in the IDE.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] For debugging functionality, Mbed Studio uses the pyOCD debug bridge software and can only debug the devices that pyOCD supports.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] The IDE itself is based on Eclipse Theia, and was designed to be easily adapted to running in a web browser -- a project that later came into existence as Keil Studio Cloud.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Mbed Studio initially supported Windows and Mac host platforms, and was later ported to run on Ubuntu Linux with its 1.0 release in June 2020.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Similar to Mbed Online Compiler, Keil Studio Cloud allows development of Mbed OS applications without installation of any development tools on the local machine.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] However, it supports many additional features, such as improved intelligent code completion functionality and built-in version control using Git.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] Unlike the Online Compiler, Keil Studio Cloud is capable of downloading to and debugging supported Mbed boards directly from the browser using WebUSB functionality.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] This allows a truly one-click build and debug experience comparable to what is offered by desktop IDEs.
[src:mbed-os/mbed] However, this functionality does not support all Mbed boards or debug probes.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A **microcontroller** (**MC**, **uC**, or **μC**) or **microcontroller unit** (**MCU**) is a small computer on a single integrated circuit.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A microcontroller contains one or more processor cores along with memory and programmable input/output peripherals.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Program memory in the form of NOR flash, OTP ROM, or ferroelectric RAM is also often included on the chip, as well as a small amount of RAM.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are designed for embedded applications, in contrast to the microprocessors used in personal computers or other general-purpose applications consisting of various discrete chips.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In modern terminology, a microcontroller is similar to, but less sophisticated than, a system on a chip (SoC).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A SoC may include a microcontroller as one of its components but usually integrates it with advanced peripherals like a graphics processing unit (GPU), a Wi-Fi module, or one or more coprocessors.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers are used in automatically controlled products and devices, such as automobile engine control systems, implantable medical devices, remote controls, office machines, appliances, power tools, toys, and other embedded systems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] By reducing the size and cost compared to a design that uses a separate microprocessor, memory, and input/output devices, microcontrollers make digital control of more devices and processes practical.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Mixed-signal microcontrollers are common, integrating analog components needed to control non-digital electronic systems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In the context of the Internet of things, microcontrollers are an economical and popular means of data collection, sensing and actuating the physical world as edge devices.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers may use four-bit words and operate at frequencies as low as 4 kHz for low power consumption (single-digit milliwatts or microwatts).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] They generally have the ability to retain functionality while waiting for an event such as a button press or other interrupt; power consumption while sleeping (with the CPU clock and most peripherals off) may be just nanowatts, making many of them well suited for long lasting battery applications.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Other microcontrollers may serve performance-critical roles, where they may need to act more like a digital signal processor (DSP), with higher clock speeds and power consumption.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released on a single MOS LSI chip in 1971.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] It was followed by the 4-bit Intel 4040, the 8-bit Intel 8008, and the 8-bit Intel 8080.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] All of these processors required several external chips to implement a working system, including memory and peripheral interface chips.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] As a result, the total system cost was several hundred (1970s US) dollars, making it impossible to economically computerize small appliances.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] MOS Technology introduced its sub-$100 microprocessors in 1975, the 6501 and 6502.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Their chief aim was to reduce this cost barrier but these microprocessors still required external support, memory, and peripheral chips which kept the total system cost in the hundreds of dollars.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] One book credits TI engineers Gary Boone and Michael Cochran with the successful creation of the first microcontroller in 1971.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The result of their work was the TMS 1000, which became commercially available in 1974.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] It combined read-only memory, read/write memory, processor and clock on one chip and was targeted at embedded systems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] During the early-to-mid-1970s, Japanese electronics manufacturers began producing microcontrollers for automobiles, including 4-bit MCUs for in-car entertainment, automatic wipers, electronic locks, and dashboard, and 8-bit MCUs for engine control.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Partly in response to the existence of the single-chip TMS 1000, Intel developed a computer system on a chip optimized for control applications, the Intel 8048, with commercial parts first shipping in 1977.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] It combined RAM and ROM on the same chip with a microprocessor.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Among numerous applications, this chip would eventually find its way into over one billion PC keyboards.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Valenter, stated that the microcontroller was one of the most successful products in the company's history, and he expanded the microcontroller division's budget by over 25%.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Most microcontrollers at this time had concurrent variants.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] One had EPROM program memory, with a transparent quartz window in the lid of the package to allow it to be erased by exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] These erasable chips were often used for prototyping.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The other variant was either a mask-programmed ROM or a PROM variant which was only programmable once.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] For the latter, sometimes the designation *OTP* was used, standing for "one-time programmable".
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In an OTP microcontroller, the PROM was usually of identical type as the EPROM, but the chip package had no quartz window; because there was no way to expose the EPROM to ultraviolet light, it could not be erased.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Because the erasable versions required ceramic packages with quartz windows, they were significantly more expensive than the OTP versions, which could be made in lower-cost opaque plastic packages.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] For the erasable variants, quartz was required, instead of less expensive glass, for its transparency to ultraviolet light—to which glass is largely opaque—but the main cost differentiator was the ceramic package itself.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] **Piggyback microcontrollers** were also used.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In 1993, the introduction of EEPROM memory allowed microcontrollers (beginning with the Microchip PIC16C84) to be electrically erased quickly without an expensive package as required for EPROM, allowing both rapid prototyping, and in-system programming.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] (EEPROM technology had been available prior to this time, but the earlier EEPROM was more expensive and less durable, making it unsuitable for low-cost mass-produced microcontrollers.) The same year, Atmel introduced the first microcontroller using Flash memory, a special type of EEPROM.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Other companies rapidly followed suit, with both memory types.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Nowadays microcontrollers are cheap and readily available for hobbyists, with large online communities around certain processors.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In 2002, about 55% of all CPUs sold in the world were 8-bit microcontrollers and microprocessors.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Over two billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 1997, and according to Semico, over four billion 8-bit microcontrollers were sold in 2006.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] More recently, Semico has claimed the MCU market grew 36.5% in 2010 and 12% in 2011.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A typical home in a developed country is likely to have only four general-purpose microprocessors but around three dozen microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A typical mid-range automobile has about 30 microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] They can also be found in many electrical devices such as washing machines, microwave ovens, and telephones.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Cost to manufacture can be under US$0.10 per unit.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Cost has plummeted over time, with the cheapest 8-bit microcontrollers being available for under US$0.03 in 2018, and some 32-bit microcontrollers around US$1 for similar quantities.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In 2012, following a global crisis—a worst ever annual sales decline and recovery and average sales price year-over-year plunging 17%—the biggest reduction since the 1980s—the average price for a microcontroller was US$0.88 (US$0.69 for 4-/8-bit, US$0.59 for 16-bit, US$1.76 for 32-bit).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In 2012, worldwide sales of 8-bit microcontrollers were around US$4 billion, while 4-bit microcontrollers also saw significant sales.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] On 21 June 2018, the "world's smallest computer" was announced by the University of Michigan.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Because they are too small to have conventional radio antennae, they receive and transmit data with visible light.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A microcontroller can be considered a self-contained system with a processor, memory and peripherals and can be used as an embedded system.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The majority of microcontrollers in use today are embedded in other machinery, such as automobiles, telephones, appliances, and peripherals for computer systems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] While some embedded systems are very sophisticated, many have minimal requirements for memory and program length, with no operating system, and low software complexity.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Typical input and output devices include switches, relays, solenoids, LEDs, small or custom liquid-crystal displays, radio frequency devices, and sensors for data such as temperature, humidity, light level etc.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Embedded systems usually have no keyboard, screen, disks, printers, or other recognizable I/O devices of a personal computer, and may lack human interaction devices of any kind.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers must provide real-time (predictable, though not necessarily fast) response to events in the embedded system they are controlling.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Possible interrupt sources are device-dependent and often include events such as an internal timer overflow, completing an analog-to-digital conversion, a logic-level change on an input such as from a button being pressed, and data received on a communication link.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Where power consumption is important as in battery devices, interrupts may also wake a microcontroller from a low-power sleep state where the processor is halted until required to do something by a peripheral event.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Typically microcontroller programs must fit in the available on-chip memory, since it would be costly to provide a system with external, expandable memory.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Compilers and assemblers are used to convert both high-level and assembly language code into a compact machine code for storage in the microcontroller's memory.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Depending on the device, the program memory may be permanent, read-only memory that can only be programmed at the factory, or it may be field-alterable flash or erasable read-only memory.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Manufacturers have often produced special versions of their microcontrollers in order to help the hardware and software development of the target system.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Originally these included EPROM versions that have a "window" on the top of the device through which program memory can be erased by ultraviolet light, ready for reprogramming after a programming ("burn") and test cycle.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Since 1998, EPROM versions are rare and have been replaced by EEPROM and flash, which are easier to use (can be erased electronically) and cheaper to manufacture.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Other versions may be available where the ROM is accessed as an external device rather than as internal memory, however these are becoming rare due to the widespread availability of cheap microcontroller programmers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The use of field-programmable devices on a microcontroller may allow field update of the firmware or permit late factory revisions to products that have been assembled but not yet shipped.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Programmable memory also reduces the lead time required for deployment of a new product.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Where hundreds of thousands of identical devices are required, using parts programmed at the time of manufacture can be economical.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] These "mask-programmed" parts have the program laid down in the same way as the logic of the chip, at the same time.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A customized microcontroller incorporates a block of digital logic that can be personalized for additional processing capability, peripherals and interfaces that are adapted to the requirements of the application.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers usually contain from several to dozens of general purpose input/output pins (GPIO).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] GPIO pins are software configurable to either an input or an output state.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] When GPIO pins are configured to an input state, they are often used to read sensors or external signals.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Configured to the output state, GPIO pins can drive external devices such as LEDs or motors, often indirectly, through external power electronics.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Many embedded systems need to read sensors that produce analog signals.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] However, because they are built to interpret and process digital data, i.e.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] 1s and 0s, they are not able to do anything with the analog signals that may be sent to it by a device.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] So, an analog-to-digital converter (ADC) is used to convert the incoming data into a form that the processor can recognize.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A less common feature on some microcontrollers is a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) that allows the processor to output analog signals or voltage levels.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In addition to the converters, many embedded microprocessors include a variety of timers as well.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] One of the most common types of timers is the programmable interval timer (PIT).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A PIT may either count down from some value to zero, or up to the capacity of the count register, overflowing to zero.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Once it reaches zero, it sends an interrupt to the processor indicating that it has finished counting.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] This is useful for devices such as thermostats, which periodically test the temperature around them to see if they need to turn the air conditioner on/off, the heater on/off, etc.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A dedicated pulse-width modulation (PWM) block makes it possible for the CPU to control power converters, resistive loads, motors, etc., without using many CPU resources in tight timer loops.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A universal asynchronous receiver/transmitter (UART) block makes it possible to receive and transmit data over a serial line with very little load on the CPU.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Dedicated on-chip hardware also often includes capabilities to communicate with other devices (chips) in digital formats such as Inter-Integrated Circuit (I²C), Serial Peripheral Interface (SPI), Universal Serial Bus (USB), and Ethernet.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers may not implement an external address or data bus as they integrate RAM and non-volatile memory on the same chip as the CPU.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Using fewer pins, the chip can be placed in a much smaller, cheaper package.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Integrating the memory and other peripherals on a single chip and testing them as a unit increases the cost of that chip, but often results in decreased net cost of the embedded system as a whole.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] This integration drastically reduces the number of chips and the amount of wiring and circuit board space that would be needed to produce equivalent systems using separate chips.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Furthermore, on low pin count devices in particular, each pin may interface to several internal peripherals, with the pin function selected by software.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] This allows a part to be used in a wider variety of applications than if pins had dedicated functions.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers have proved to be highly popular in embedded systems since their introduction in the 1970s.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers use a Harvard architecture: separate memory buses for instructions and data, allowing accesses to take place concurrently.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Where a Harvard architecture is used, instruction words for the processor may be a different bit size than the length of internal memory and registers; for example: 12-bit instructions used with 8-bit data registers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The decision of which peripheral to integrate is often difficult.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The microcontroller vendors often trade operating frequencies and system design flexibility against time-to-market requirements from their customers and overall lower system cost.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Manufacturers have to balance the need to minimize the chip size against additional functionality.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontroller architectures vary widely.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Some designs include general-purpose microprocessor cores, with one or more ROM, RAM, or I/O functions integrated onto the package.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Other designs are purpose-built for control applications.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A microcontroller instruction set usually has many instructions intended for bit manipulation (bit-wise operations) to make control programs more compact.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] For example, a general-purpose processor might require several instructions to test a bit in a register and branch if the bit is set, where a microcontroller could have a single instruction to provide that commonly required function.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers historically have not had math coprocessors, so floating-point arithmetic has been performed by software.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] However, some recent designs do include FPUs and DSP-optimized features.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] An example would be Microchip's PIC32 MIPS-based line.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers were originally programmed only in assembly language, but various high-level programming languages, such as C, Python and JavaScript, are now also in common use to target microcontrollers and embedded systems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Compilers for general-purpose languages will typically have some restrictions as well as enhancements to better support the unique characteristics of microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Some microcontrollers have environments to aid developing certain types of applications.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontroller vendors often make tools freely available to make it easier to adopt their hardware.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Microcontrollers with specialty hardware may require their own non-standard dialects of C, such as SDCC for the 8051, which prevent using standard tools (such as code libraries or static analysis tools) even for code unrelated to hardware features.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Interpreters may also contain nonstandard features, such as MicroPython, although a fork, CircuitPython, has looked to move hardware dependencies to libraries and have the language adhere to a more CPython standard.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Interpreter firmware is also available for some microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] For example, BASIC on the early microcontroller Intel 8052; BASIC and FORTH on the Zilog Z8 as well as some modern devices.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Typically these interpreters support interactive programming.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Simulators are available for some microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] These allow a developer to analyze what the behavior of the microcontroller and their program should be if they were using the actual part.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A simulator will show the internal processor state and also that of the outputs, as well as allowing input signals to be generated.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] While on the one hand most simulators will be limited from being unable to simulate much other hardware in a system, they can exercise conditions that may otherwise be hard to reproduce at will in the physical implementation, and can be the quickest way to debug and analyze problems.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Recent microcontrollers are often integrated with on-chip debug circuitry that when accessed by an in-circuit emulator (ICE) via JTAG, allow debugging of the firmware with a debugger.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A real-time ICE may allow viewing and/or manipulating of internal states while running.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A tracing ICE can record executed program and MCU states before/after a trigger point.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Many others exist, some of which are used in very narrow range of applications or are more like applications processors than microcontrollers.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The microcontroller market is extremely fragmented, with numerous vendors, technologies, and markets.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Note that many vendors sell or have sold multiple architectures.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In contrast to general-purpose computers, microcontrollers used in embedded systems often seek to optimize interrupt latency over instruction throughput.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Issues include both reducing the latency, and making it be more predictable (to support real-time control).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] When an electronic device causes an interrupt, during the context switch the intermediate results (registers) have to be saved before the software responsible for handling the interrupt can run.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] They must also be restored after that interrupt handler is finished.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] If there are more processor registers, this saving and restoring process may take more time, increasing the latency.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Another technique involves spending silicon gates on "shadow registers": One or more duplicate registers used only by the interrupt software, perhaps supporting a dedicated stack.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Lower end microcontrollers tend to support fewer interrupt latency controls than higher end ones.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Two different kinds of memory are commonly used with microcontrollers, a non-volatile memory for storing firmware and a read–write memory for temporary data.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] From the earliest microcontrollers to today, six-transistor SRAM is almost always used as the read/write working memory, with a few more transistors per bit used in the register file.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] In addition to the SRAM, some microcontrollers also have internal EEPROM and/or NVRAM for data storage; and ones that do not have any (such as the BASIC Stamp), or where the internal memory is insufficient, are often connected to an external EEPROM or flash memory chip.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] A few microcontrollers beginning in 2003 have "self-programmable" flash memory.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] The earliest microcontrollers used mask ROM to store firmware.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Later microcontrollers (such as the early versions of the Freescale 68HC11 and early PIC microcontrollers) had EPROM memory, which used a translucent window to allow erasure via UV light, while production versions had no such window, being OTP (one-time-programmable).
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Firmware updates were equivalent to replacing the microcontroller itself, thus many products were not upgradeable.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Motorola MC68HC805 was the first microcontroller to use EEPROM to store the firmware.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] EEPROM microcontrollers became more popular in 1993 when Microchip introduced PIC16C84 and Atmel introduced an 8051-core microcontroller that was first one to use NOR Flash memory to store the firmware.
[src:mbed-os/microcontroller] Today's microcontrollers almost all use flash memory, with a few models using FRAM and some ultra-low-cost parts still using OTP or mask ROM.
